The layman is not to be blamed for holding ideas that were largely conveyed to him, either directly or indirectly, by scientists who were themselves addicted to these erroneous ideas. The biologists of the nineteenth century, and many of their leading interpreters, were largely responsible for the spread of these erroneous notions, while, paradoxically enough,
